28:14.275 --> 28:17.959
would be it. So in other words, we were free. The 
only thing that would stop us is weather, and that

28:20.782 --> 28:36.019
was one of the main reasons because during that 
year that they were planning, they also had a plan

28:20.782 --> 28:36.019
at what time when what month they would have they 
would go because during the July and August season

28:35.999 --> 28:59.610
is where the typhoon season and unlucky for us we 
didn't know that so we chose that month to go and so

28:35.999 --> 28:59.610
it took us seven day in the open sea and the four the 
first The first day was really calm, but the next

28:59.590 --> 29:09.860
four days was just all thunderstorm, typhoon, and 
all that, the four days. And we thought that we

29:10.200 --> 29:19.208
would not make it because the boat was just going, 
the wave was just slapping the boat side by side,

29:10.200 --> 29:19.208
side by side, and all that. And in order for us to 
keep the boat from going over, from flipping over

29:26.455 --> 29:36.194
was a whole bunch of people had to go down to the 
fishing compartment to stay there so that the

29:26.455 --> 29:36.194
balance would be even. And in other words, in the 
cabin there would be Only three men and a

29:39.415 --> 29:51.229
couple of kids and my mom would stay in the cabin. 
One would navigate, one would steer the boat, and

29:51.909 --> 29:59.398
the other would feed the person that steered. And 
the kids that are in the cabin would lay down so that

29:59.918 --> 30:09.169
you want the boat to be evenly weight so that you 
would not have one weight on one side so that it

30:09.149 --> 30:13.456
would be so easy to flip over. So y'all were on rough 
waters. Rough water, real. Once we got out in the

30:20.388 --> 30:23.733
open water, everybody was down. I mean, we were all 
sick already right there because when, you know,

30:23.873 --> 30:34.431
at the part where you go from the port out in the open 
water, it's really a lot of waves, and... The boat

30:34.968 --> 30:43.300
was shaking already right there, and so we were not 
used to it yet because I, for one, have not even

30:34.968 --> 30:43.300
stepped on a boat before. So we got sick right 
there, right away. So actually, only the last two

30:46.144 --> 30:53.074
days were the days that we were really fine. 
Otherwise, all the other days, we were gone. Okay,

30:55.478 --> 30:58.242
where did you go from... from there outside of the 
port? I went from the port. We went all the way to to

31:07.469 --> 31:09.150
the main Thailand. The main Thailand had little 
beachfront that so many refugees had escaped that

31:09.731 --> 31:26.065
they would just, when their boat was in emergency, 
like they had a hold, they would just dump their

31:09.731 --> 31:26.065
boat right on the shore. And they would just say, 
ha, this is where the place we're going to stay. And

31:29.308 --> 31:33.432
so many people did that, that it became a refugee 
camp. And so all along the Thailand coast, shore

31:37.490 --> 32:00.949
this all along the thailand mainland were just 
little camps everywhere that were refugees that

31:37.490 --> 32:00.949
were from escape and the majority of them were 
vietnamese that escaped because we went a year

31:37.490 --> 32:00.949
late so by the time we got there by the time that we 
got to the refuge camp that we stayed it was a really

31:37.490 --> 32:00.949
well established had more more than a hundred 
people already there you know waiting for them to

32:01.182 --> 32:29.839
be sponsored and all that so i went straight into 
one of these records uh yes we went straight into uh

32:01.182 --> 32:29.839
straight into it yeah and what happened there were 
you processed through or well at that time they the

32:01.182 --> 32:29.839
thailand government were really lenient they 
knew that a lot of people were going to do this so

32:01.182 --> 32:29.839
they would accept all the refugees to come in and 
for them to live in the camp, you know. And then we

32:37.312 --> 32:46.968
would have to give them paper, tell them what 
country we prefer to be sponsored to go to and all

32:37.312 --> 32:46.968
that. And then they would give our name to the one of 
the ambassadors of that country and he would have a

32:51.115 --> 33:00.282
list and every day, every day around around 10 
a.m., there would be guys from other countries,

33:00.785 --> 33:11.142
Canada, France, United States, West Germany, and 
all that. They would come, and they would read out

33:11.182 --> 33:17.873
their list, which one was appropriate for them to 
go. And so at that time, every day at 10, everybody

33:17.913 --> 33:25.486
would be real crowded in the front gate so that they 
would hear their name. And after they hear their

33:25.686 --> 33:27.349
name, they would have to pack and then at the end of 
the week there would be a bus to come and pick them

33:27.329 --> 33:36.960
up. And usually it would be every other week there 
would be like around 50 people. No, no, it would be

33:44.829 --> 33:50.055
around 25 people would get picked. And they would 
go to the bus and they would get transferred into

33:50.075 --> 33:57.083
the capital city of Thailand, which is Bangkok. 
And they would stay there for a couple more months

33:57.704 --> 34:07.258
for the process of the actual going to whatever 
country you wanted to go. How long were y'all in

34:08.521 --> 34:13.369
there? After we stayed in the refugee camps a 
couple days later, my mom was busy writing letters

34:13.889 --> 34:23.685
to my aunt over in Canada. My aunt in Canada, she 
lived there for 14 years. She went to school there,

34:27.511 --> 34:32.098
and she got married there, and she decided to stay 
there. My mom contacted her for money, and then my

34:32.078 --> 34:49.195
mom also contacted a couple of my dad's real good 
friends that he met while he was over in the United

34:32.078 --> 34:49.195
States in 72. And so she would contact them also to 
tell them that we are over here already, that we are

34:50.557 --> 35:01.748
waiting, and if there's any way they can help us. 
you know, please do, and all that. And so, a couple

35:03.250 --> 35:27.278
days later, my aunt would send us money for food and 
all that, and then one of my dad's friends actually

35:03.250 --> 35:27.278
went down to the island, to our place, and he would 
talk to my mom, and he would say that, you know,

35:03.250 --> 35:27.278
don't worry, we're going to get you out of here as 
soon as possible. And, uh, At the end of the month,

35:28.947 --> 35:31.190
we were gone. We were in the list. You left the 
refugee camps. Yes. So actually, we stayed at the

35:36.258 --> 35:39.883
refugee camps only one month. And after that, we 
left to Bangkok, and we stayed there. And the

35:44.450 --> 35:51.681
reason why we stayed there three months at the 
Bangkok place, the reason why we had to stay so long

35:51.661 --> 36:03.296
The reason why we had to stay so long was because we 
had to do some physical examination and see if you

35:51.661 --> 36:03.296
had any disease and a vaccination and all that. 
Just take care of yourself and all that. And the

36:06.380 --> 36:13.770
place that we were living in were an abandoned 
penitentiary. It was a really big penitentiary.

36:16.723 --> 36:19.149
And when we got there, it was really dirty. And 
there were a whole bunch of people that were

36:19.670 --> 36:27.912
already there waiting to be picked up. Everywhere 
you go, when you got there, you had to go and find

36:29.073 --> 36:35.145
yourself a place to live. So my mom and I, we would go 
down the court, go down the hall, and check out

36:35.967 --> 36:43.261
where we would go. And there would be these cells 
that have bar doors. There would be people

36:48.091 --> 36:51.515
actually living in there, and it was really dirty. 
They didn't have any bed. They had to sleep down on

36:52.517 --> 36:53.818
the floor. They provided you mattresses, but no 
bed frame. So you actually just put the mattresses

36:58.244 --> 37:03.491
on the floor, and you would just sleep there. And so 
my mom decided for us not to live in one of those

37:03.511 --> 37:10.860
cells, because there would not be air 
circulating, so that it would be real bad for us. So

37:11.340 --> 37:14.925
what we did was we lived under a staircase. so that 
there would be air circulating and all that. And so

37:19.667 --> 37:22.954
we stayed there three months, and then we got on the 
list. We had all our physical examination was off.

37:29.046 --> 37:29.787
We're all fine. So we were accepted to go. Where 
were you going to? We were going to the United

37:36.100 --> 37:46.574
States because my mom did not want to go to Canada 
because, for one thing, it was really cold over

37:36.100 --> 37:46.574
there. So she wanted us to go to the United States. 
And also, we had a relative that already left in

37:52.001 --> 37:58.429
1970. that she was already there. In fact, she was 
my dad's oldest sister, and her family were all

38:01.115 --> 38:07.610
over there. She was established in America. Yeah, 
she was already established. So we asked her if she

38:11.479 --> 38:16.570
could sponsor us, and she agreed. you had the main 
thing is the two main thing is you had to have a

38:17.107 --> 38:46.253
sponsor and you have your physical examination 
have to be good in order for you to be on the list and

38:17.107 --> 38:46.253
we didn't waste any time even though three months 
was was very long but we waited and uh we got on the

38:17.107 --> 38:46.253
list a bus came by took us and uh at this time when the 
whenever the bus come they would pick up a hundred

38:17.107 --> 38:46.253
people instead of only 25 because That place in 
Bangkok was just packed. It was just loaded of

38:50.138 --> 38:51.600
people. There were no places to stay. There were 
actually people living out in the hall that you can

38:53.843 --> 39:01.533
barely walk through it. And so they would pick up at 
least 100 people every week. And those 100 people

39:07.040 --> 39:11.566
would go to a certain place that they wanted to go. 
So it took us a couple hours to go to the airport. We

39:15.411 --> 39:18.055
got on the plane, and we flew to France. And we 
stopped there for fuel, refuel, and then we flew

39:18.576 --> 39:22.401
straight to Houston. And my aunt came and picked us 
up. Where does your aunt live? Where does she live?

39:31.333 --> 39:32.895
My aunt lives in Houston. So y'all went to live in 
Houston? Yes. We went to live with her for a couple

39:36.754 --> 39:40.861
weeks. And then we finally found... Well, she had a 
sponsor when she came over. And so what she did was

39:47.531 --> 39:56.024
she asked her sponsor if it was okay if that couple 
could be our sponsor. And that couple is a... old

39:58.863 --> 40:01.887
couple, American, an old American couple. They 
were really nice and they were really willing and

40:02.468 --> 40:07.835
happy to accept us, you know, as sponsor. And they 
took care of us. They brought us clothes, food, and

40:09.758 --> 40:19.251
found us an affordable apartment so that we could 
move out because My mom wanted us to start out by

40:19.535 --> 40:26.692
ourselves, so we only stayed with my aunt for two 
weeks, and then we were gone. We went to an

40:27.053 --> 40:29.759
apartment that we rented. So you've lived in 
Houston ever since? Yes, we live in Houston ever

40:34.090 --> 40:36.295
since. Okay, what is the status with your father? 
He didn't get out after those five years? Okay,

40:42.655 --> 41:01.084
when we got out and when we were still over here and 
it went past five years and my grandmother quickly

40:42.655 --> 41:01.084
contacted us because she knew that my mom would be 
really you know, gone berserk. So she contacted us

41:03.481 --> 41:17.233
and she said that there's something wrong, you 
know, that there seems like they're keeping the

41:03.481 --> 41:17.233
officers for a longer time because my uncle, I had 
one other uncle that was also went to

41:17.433 --> 41:19.358
concentration camp. And he stayed for only three 
years. And he got out. Was he an officer? He was a

41:25.253 --> 41:26.637
sergeant. So you had to be a really high commanding 
officer for you to be staying longer than that.

41:33.093 --> 41:43.468
Also, she said that all the other relatives have 
sons that were released, but she said that there

41:33.093 --> 41:43.468
were no high commanding officers that were 
released yet. My mom had a couple of friends that

41:44.169 --> 41:50.578
decided to stay back. instead because they wanted 
to wait for their husband because their husband

41:50.828 --> 42:15.047
because they would said that it would take only 
five years so that's not long so i'll stay and so uh

41:50.828 --> 42:15.047
her friends would come to my grandmother and would 
cry and would go you know would ask all these

41:50.828 --> 42:15.047
questions you know why why is it taking so long and 
all that how long and now they're gonna they

41:50.828 --> 42:15.047
started asking question how long Are they going to 
be kept in concentration camp? Is it going to be

42:19.206 --> 42:20.349
forever? Or when are they going to get released and 
all that? And my mom wrote back to my grandmother

42:26.762 --> 42:33.696
and said that, OK, we're doing real fine over here. 
So just keep going. just keep me updated on what's

42:37.235 --> 42:40.440
going on and all that. So my grandmother would tell 
us that everybody is just going berserk.

42:44.828 --> 42:53.682
Everybody's going to their neighbor asking if 
their husband or their sons have been released yet

42:44.828 --> 42:53.682
or did they get any letters from them yet. And then 
they would go to the headquarters and complain

42:54.103 --> 42:56.968
about it. They would say that, you know, they 
wouldn't say that it's five years and how come

42:57.288 --> 43:03.158
they're not out, but they would say, you know, How 
long are y'all going to plan to keep them and all

43:03.138 --> 43:06.622
that? And so they say that they don't know and all 
that. It's up to the head honcho and all that. Were

43:12.829 --> 43:16.012
you in any contact with your father this time? 
During that time, the contact was very little.

43:19.296 --> 43:25.322
During that time, we would receive a letter per two 
months, two months or less. So in other words, we

43:25.342 --> 43:29.567
received only six letters a whole year. But 
actually, we did not receive my dad's letter. My

43:34.636 --> 43:45.295
dad mailed it to my grandmother, and my 
grandmother would go to my aunt, and my aunt would

43:34.636 --> 43:45.295
go down to us, my aunt from Canada, because 
somehow, I don't know what it is, but somehow the

43:45.275 --> 43:54.848
mail seems to circulate faster if you go that way. 
Because I have no idea why, but that's how we... At

43:55.349 --> 44:02.318
the first time, at the beginning, we did that. But 
then later on, we mailed straight from Vietnam all

44:02.859 --> 44:12.312
the way down to Houston, which when we opened the 
letter, we would read, you know, It was in June, and

44:12.764 --> 44:17.109
we would receive it all the way until September. So 
it would take around three months for the letter to

44:17.770 --> 44:21.314
arrive. Well, anyway, the wives were getting 
really crazy. They were getting worried. Now they

44:27.420 --> 44:41.556
were getting worried that if they would ever had a 
chance to escape because later on there were less

44:27.420 --> 44:41.556
and less people escaping because there were 
bandits. out in the open sea. They knew that there

44:43.516 --> 44:47.385
were refugees going to escape. So they knew that. 
So they were waiting out there so that if they see

44:48.608 --> 44:53.098
any boat, they would come and they would take the 
valuables, rape the women, and take all the food

44:53.534 --> 45:01.244
and all that. So if you waited around for your 
husband to be released, you didn't have much money

45:01.825 --> 45:09.695
to leave after that. Actually, those wives that 
had their husbands that were still in the past five

45:09.715 --> 45:20.149
years, they they just forget about the escape 
because they knew that there was just no way

45:20.129 --> 45:31.000
because it was just way too late now for them to 
escape.

